== Chiefdom of Maguana ==
[[Image:Maguana.JPG|thumb|300px|right|cacique of Maguana]]
The cacique of Maguana (''cacicazgo of Maguana'') was the center of the Quisqueya island, bounded on the north by the caciques of Mari<U+00E9>n and Magu<U+00E1>, south by the Caribbean, east by the caciques of Magu<U+00E1> and Hig<U+00FC>ey, and west by the caciques of Mari<U+00E9>n and Jaragua. This cacique only covered the territories of the current Dominican Republic].

It was ruled by the cacique [[Caonabo]], husband of [[Anacaona]]. Its headquarters was established at the place called [[Corral de los Indios]] in [[Juan de Herrera (Dominican Republic)|Juan de Herrera]] of [[San Juan de la Maguana|San Juan]]. It was divided into 21 nita<U+00ED>nos. This province is devoted to the art of war.

This was the principal cacique of the island and was represented by "Peter". The term ''Maguana'' means "the first stone, the unique stone". His mother goddess was apito, which means "Mother of Stone".<ref>{{es}} [http://maguana.net/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=48:historia&catid=36:historia&limitstart=1&Itemid=56 Maguana.net]</ref>

The cacique Caonabo was the first resistance against the Spanish occupation. This chief is accused of being responsible for the destruction of Fort [[La Navidad]], the first Spanish settlement on American soil, installed by [[Christopher Columbus]] to the inability to repatriate all of his men to Spain during his first voyage. Because of this attack and the attempted assault of [[Fort Saint-Thomas]], Caonabo was taken prisoner. [[Alonso de Ojeda]] tricked him into believing that he would offer her golden shackles.{{clarify|date=September 2011}} Caonabo was handcuffed and transferred to [[La Isabela]], then sent to Spain. The chief died in a shipwreck while crossing.<ref>{{es}} [http://www.maguana.net Maguana.net]</ref>

